Comment: Well done if you got 2. d5! 1.....c5 is an inferior way of playing the Benoni Defence. 1. d4 Nf3 2. c4 c5 is better as, compared to the game continuation, White has made a non-developing pawn move(2. c4). White has the c4 square for a Knight or Bishop and is also able to play Bb5+ at some stage. 2. d5 is the most aggressive way of playing for White, so nothing for anything else.
Well done if you found this! I will also give a point for 3. e4 which will transpose.
There was a big hint last time! I will also give a point for Nf3
I wanted to capture on e6 without allowing his Bishop to recapture.
Big clue last move. Nothing for anything else.
Nothing for anything else. White has a space advantage, wants to prevent Black playing d5. If Black can be induced to play e5, he is very weak on the a2-g8 diagonal.
White doesn't want the Bc4 knocked of the wonderful a2-g8 diagonal
White continues his development and stops Black from playing Nd5.
A point for 0-0 also. White attacks d6, hoping to induce e5
I think the Bishop belongs on this diagonal, so nothing for anything else.
